Democracy summit ends, Biden says the fire of freedom will never go out
The online “Summit for Democracy” (Summit for Democracy) (Summit for Democracy) convened by US President Joe Biden and attended by 110 governments around the world, as well as civil society and private sector leaders, ended on Friday (December 10).
Biden said in his closing remarks that the fire of freedom burns in the hearts of everyone in the world and that authoritarian regimes will never be able to extinguish it.
He also said that he plans to hold the 2nd global “democracy summit” next year.
Taiwan government representative and government councilor Tang Feng, and Hong Kong democracy and human rights activist Luo Guancong, who is currently in exile in the UK, also spoke at the summit the next day.
Biden said, “We know how arduous the work ahead of us is.
But we also know that we can rise to the challenge, because as I have said before, as this summit has shown, the democratic world is ubiquitous.
Authoritarian regimes will never be able to extinguish the flames of freedom that are burning in the hearts of people all over the world and around the world. ”
Biden also said defending democracy requires the joint efforts of the whole society.
“As government leaders, we have a responsibility to listen to our citizens, strengthen the guardrails of democracy, push for reform, achieve transparent and accountable governance, forces that are more resistant to the buffers and shocks of authoritarianism, and those who want to blatantly pursue power before the public interest,” he said. ”
The themes of the second day of the “Democracy Summit” were defending human rights, consolidating democracy and confronting authoritarianism, and countering digital authoritarianism and affirming democratic values.
This day coincides with “International Human Rights Day”.
UN Secretary General Guterres also said in his opening speech that day that the cause of democracy faces challenges around the world, especially those brought about by emerging digital technologies.
“Now is the time to reaffirm common values and positions and democratic resilience,” he said.
This requires deepening social dialogue, addressing inequalities, fighting corruption, renewing the social contract, investing in quality education and expanding opportunities for women and girls.
It also requires a firm condemnation of populism, nativism and extremism in all its forms, including the use of all the tools offered by the technological revolution. ”
Hong Kong democracy and human rights activist Luo Guancong addressed the summit via a pre-recorded video, reminding participants to continue to pay attention to the human rights situation in Hong Kong and Chinese ethnic minorities such as Uyghurs and Tibetans.
“For a long time, the world has always been affected by the rise of China, but no mechanism has been established to hold it accountable,” he said.
That is why politicians and civil society leaders must work together.
We must use everything we have (resources) to ensure that the restoration of democracy is our top priority. ”
Luo Guancong also called on the free world to unite against the CCP's threat.
He said, “Maybe some of you are afraid to annoy General Secretary Xi Jinping, maybe some of you don't want to lose the Chinese market, or maybe some of you don't realize the threat [the Chinese Communist Party] is to our democratic values.
And that's why we failed.
That's why we have to change. ”
While attending a roundtable discussion on “Combating Digital Dictatorship and Affirming Democratic Values”, Tang Feng, government member of Taiwan's Executive Yuan, released the “National Statement” via video, emphasizing that Taiwan is at the forefront of confronting authoritarianism and authoritarianism.
He also shared his experience on how to fight COVID-19 through transparency of information and building mutual trust.
He said, “At a time when democracy in Taiwan is on the rise, we have always firmly stood at the forefront of the global fight against authoritarianism and played a leading role in promoting global freedom, democracy and human rights.
During the pandemic, authoritarian governments everywhere rationalized human rights violations in the name of public health and the collective interest, and global democracy showed signs of regression.
However, in Taiwan, we don't have to close the city to control the epidemic, and we can overcome fake information without being removed from the shelves. ”
At the same time as the schedule for the second day of the “Democracy Summit” was underway, the US Treasury Department announced that it would impose sanctions on 15 individuals and 10 entities from several countries, including China and North Korea, who were found to have committed serious human rights violations, in accordance with the law, and imposed investment restrictions on a Chinese company recognized as using surveillance technology to assist in human rights violations.
