Vietnam People's Daily - Gulf Cooperation Council responds to common challenges
Saudi Crown Prince Mohammed bin Salman's stops include Oman, the United Arab Emirates (UAE), Qatar, Bahrain, and Kuwait.
Notably, this is Crown Prince Mohammed's first visit to Qatar since Saudi Arabia and its Arab allies imposed an embargo on Qatar in mid-2017, leading to the diplomatic crisis in the Gulf.
In the midst of this crisis, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, Bahrain, and Egypt severed diplomatic relations with Qatar and imposed a total embargo on it, accusing Qatar of supporting terrorist organizations and close ties with Iran.
Diplomatic tensions have seriously affected the internal unity of the GCC and have had a negative impact on the economies of the countries of the region.
Four Arab countries blocked land, sea and air routes to Qatar.
The crisis was only resolved at the Gulf Cooperation Council summit in January 2021, when the Gulf countries signed an agreement mediated by the United States and Kuwait to move towards “unity and stability.”
Saudi Arabia has reopened its border with Qatar.
Saudi Arabia and Egypt are spearheading efforts to restore relations with Qatar through the appointment of new ambassadors in Qatar by the two countries.
The Arab countries of the Gulf to resolve their differences in order to restore relations with Qatar stem from the need to unite for the benefit of all countries and regional stability, with the aim of meeting common challenges.
During the Saudi Crown Prince's visit to Oman this time, the two sides agreed to open the first direct land passage between the two Gulf neighbors.
The 725-kilometer corridor connecting the two countries will facilitate the travel and integration of supply chains for citizens of the two countries.
Saudi Arabia's Public Investment Fund (PIF) will invest US$5 billion in Oman, and companies from the two countries have signed 13 memorandums of understanding on cooperation worth US$30 billion.
The Saudi Crown Prince's visit to the Gulf countries coincided with negotiations between Iran and the world's major powers to salvage the Iran nuclear deal known as the Joint Comprehensive Action Plan (JCPOA) — an agreement condemned by the Gulf Arab countries for believing it impossible to resolve the missile issue with Iran.
The Gulf countries have always regarded Iran as a long-term “competitor” and Iran's nuclear program as a “threat” to regional security.
The Gulf countries believe that it is flawed not to resolve the Iranian missile issue and to take no action to curb Iran's activities in the region.
Saudi Arabia and Iran engaged in direct negotiations against the backdrop of nuclear negotiations between major powers and Iran failing to meet the wishes of the Gulf countries.
The goal is to contain the escalation of tension in the region.
This is one of the factors slowing the economic growth of the GCC countries.
