Don't scare people off at the starting line-Xinhua
When I visit the book market, I often feel the popularity of books on successful studies.
Many of today's success studies books promote the “best principle” — that is, assume or imply that you can “do it” first, and then tell “what” you need to do.
It's tantamount to saying that all of a sudden we have crossed the “how to do it”, which is actually the most important and fundamental link.
Because of this, these books all have a common characteristic — either you work hard to your best, or you just don't do anything; it's 100, or it's 0; or you climb Mount Taishan, or you just stay where you are.
This kind of “best principle” makes anyone who sees it admit to being “extremely correct”, but 99% of people will be intimidated by the starting line.
Because this theory advocates a path of “you have to make up your mind, become a human again, and make a big 180-degree transformation”, and this is precisely the Achilles heel of many people.
For people who stick to the rules, follow the old, and refuse to change, you prefer to shout “You want to change” in his ear, which is undoubtedly an act of deceiving oneself and playing piano against cattle.
The vast majority of people are timid in the face of the word “transformation”, and it is difficult to make up their minds; or they decide to “change” with a momentary impulse and pain, and bravely take the first step, but often the good picture is not long, and they lose the battle without persisting for a while, and it is difficult to see sustainability.
Mr. Ma Sanli's famous comic “Starting Tomorrow” is the most evocative expression of this classic of “universal humanity”.
The biggest problem with the “best principle” is that the threshold is too high. It often exceeds the limits of the abilities of ordinary people, causing the vast majority of people to “look at the door and sigh.”
Perhaps the “second best principle” is a way that is likely to allow more ordinary people to embark on a path of relative success.
The core of the “second best principle” is “lowering the threshold” — it encourages the theory of “winning small wins big wins”, that is, if you can't do 100, just do 1: because 1 is never greater than 0; if you can't climb Mount Taishan, you can just climb the small sand dune at your doorstep, because that's always better than stepping where you are.
In short, as long as you do something, it's better than not doing it.
Since the threshold has been drastically lowered, it is more likely that ordinary people will persist, and as long as they persist in everything, the probability of success will also increase.
It's just that the path to success following the “second best principle” is a bit longer.
All in all, the “best principle”, although ostensibly under the banner of making everyone successful, is actually a minority that it can ultimately inspire; and the “second best principle” can effectively motivate more people and benefit as many people as possible.
The reserves of bare carp resources in Qinghai Lake increased by 71,000 tons this year.-Xinhua
Xinhua News Agency, Xining, December 11 (Reporters Luo Xiaofei and Zhang Hongxiang) - The reporter learned from the Qinghai Provincial Department of Agriculture and Rural Affairs that the latest monitoring results show that the bare carp resource reserves of Qinghai Lake increased by 71,000 tons this year over the previous year to 108,500 tons. Compared with the beginning of protection in 2002, a cumulative increase of more than 40 times.
Qinghai Lake bare carp, commonly known as “mackerel”, is a precious fish species unique to Qinghai Lake. It plays an important role in maintaining the safety and biodiversity of the “water-fish-bird” ecological chain in the Qinghai Lake Basin.
In the sixties and seventies of the 20th century, the number of bare carp in Qinghai Lake declined sharply due to factors such as mass manslaughter and the deteriorating environment in the breeding waters of bare carp. In 2002, the bare carp resource reserves in Qinghai Lake were only 2,592 tons.
In 2004, naked carp from Qinghai Lake was listed as an endangered species in the “Red List of Chinese Species”.
Since 2003, Qinghai Province has imposed a closure on the lake to raise fish. It prohibits any unit, group or individual from fishing for naked carp in Qinghai Lake and the main rivers and tributaries of the Lake District, and prohibits the sale of bare carp and its products.
At the same time, protection efforts have been continuously increased through measures such as artificial breeding and discharging, cleaning up the main rivers entering the lake in Qinghai Lake, and scientifically and reasonably designed “fish crossing channels”. The reserves of bare carp resources in Qinghai Lake are increasing year by year.
Yang Lin, deputy director of the Qinghai Provincial Department of Agriculture and Rural Affairs, explained that up to now, nearly 180 million tails of bare carp in Qinghai Lake have been artificially bred and discharged, contributing more than 23 percent to the recovery of bare carp resources in Qinghai Lake.
The source area of the three rivers of Qinghai is an important ecological barrier and water conservation area in China and even Asia, while Qinghai Lake is a natural barrier and ecological functional area to control the eastward spread of desertification in the west.
In order to protect the ecological environment of the source area of the three rivers and the waters of Qinghai Lake, protect aquatic wildlife, and maintain the biodiversity of the Qinghai-Tibet Plateau, since this year, Qinghai has successively issued anti-fishing notices in key waters of the Yangtze River, the Yellow River and the Qinghai Lake, and has established a “one river, one river, one lake” comprehensive ban management system.
